    "from nltk.corpus import state_union\n",
    "from nltk.tokenize import  PunktSentenceTokenizer\n",
    "from string import punctuation\n",
    "import re\n",

   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Tokenize the required data ### "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def tokenize_text(corpus):\n",
    "\n",
    "    wnl = WordNetLemmatizer()\n",
    "    \n",
    "    POS_sents = sent_tokenize(corpus) # tags sents\n",
    "    \n",
    "    POS_words = [word_tokenize(sent) for sent in POS_sents]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    tagged_POS_sents = [nltk.pos_tag(sent) for sent in POS_words]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    cleaned=[]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    for sent in tagged_POS_sents:\n",
    "        normed_tagged_words = [word.lower for word in sent \n",
    "                               if word.lower() not in nltk.corpus.stopwords.words('english')\n",
    "                               and word not in punctuation # remove punctuation\n",
    "                               and not re.search(r'''^[\\.,;\"'?!():\\-_`]+$''', word)\n",
    "                                and len(word)>=4]\n",
    "        cleaned.extend(normed_tagged_words)\n",
    "        \n",
    "    return cleaned\n",
    "        \n",
    "y_label=[]\n",
    "x_label=[]\n",
    "for i in data[\"Review Text\"]:\n",
    "    a=tokenize_text(str(i))\n",
    "    x_label.append(a)\n",
    "\n",
    "      \n",
    "    \n",
    "\n",
    "    "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "x_label"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Get the lemma the tokenized word whose tag begins with NN/VB/RB/JJ###"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def lemma(sents): #Lemmatizing the  words \n",
    "    tagged_POS_sents = [nltk.pos_tag(sent) for sent in sents]\n",
    "    lemma= WordNetLemmatizer()\n",
    "    word_lemma=[]\n",
    "    for sent in tagged_POS_sents:\n",
    "        intermediary=[]\n",
    "        for word in sent: # Lemmatising according to the POS to maintain integrity of meaning\n",
    "            if word[1][:2] == \"NN\" or word[1][:2] == \"JJ\" or word[1][:2] == \"VB\" or word[1][:2] == \"RB\":  \n",
    "                lemma_tag = {'NN':wordnet.NOUN,'JJ':wordnet.ADJ,'VB':wordnet.VERB,'RB':wordnet.ADV}\n",
    "                intermediary.append(lemma.lemmatize(word[0], pos=lemma_tag[word[1][:2]]))\n",
    "            else:\n",
    "                intermediary.append(lemma.lemmatize(word[0]))\n",
    "        word_lemma.append(intermediary)\n",
    "    return word_lemma\n",
    "                                  \n",
    "a= lemma(x_label)"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "def nn_vb_jj(lemmatised_pos):   # use NN,VB,JJ as the feature word\n",
    "    print \n",
    "    a= [x[0] for x in lemmatised_pos if x[1] ==\"VB\" or x[1] ==\"NN\" or x[1] == \"JJ\"]\n",
    "    return a\n",
    "x_train=[]\n",
    "for i in lemmatised_pos:\n",
    "    a= nn_vb_jj(i)\n",
    "    x_train.append(a)\n",
    "x_train"
   ]
  },

    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "### Brief Team Work ###"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "1. Xuancheng built a test version with basic structure and simple algorithm to do the first submit.\n",
    "2. Suran and Xuancheng respectively tried different methods\n",
    "3. Suran's version got a better result at first.\n",
    "4. Based on Suran's version, Xuancheng tested different feature and different setting and got the final result\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Member's effort (except those in team work) ###"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Suran ####"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": []
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Xuancheng ####"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "1. My original thoght is to use wn.path_similarity to test the similarity of word to the keywords of 6 categories. For example, \"hair\" & \"salon\" would have a close distance to \"body\". So the review include these 2 words are likely to be classified as \"Beauty & Bath\".\n",
    "    Below is the function I use:\n",
    "$$\n",
    "def distance_feature(x, keyword):\n",
    "    try:\n",
    "        termlist = freq_normed_unigrams(x)# get top unigrams\n",
    "        distance = []\n",
    "        for term in termlist:                  # for each term\n",
    "            s = wn.synsets(term)               # get its nominal synsets\n",
    "            for syn in s:                   # for each lemma synset   \n",
    "                c = wn.path_similarity(wn.synset(syn.name()), wn.synset(keyword))\n",
    "                if c != None:\n",
    "                    distance.append(c)\n",
    "        if distance == []:\n",
    "            return 0\n",
    "        return max(distance)    \n",
    "    except TypeError:\n",
    "        return 0\n",
    "$$        \n",
    "2. However, the algorithm's expense is greatly huge. It usually need a whole night to get a accuracy result. And moreover, if using naive bayes, the result is not good enought.\n",
    "3. Thus, then I tried KNN but the algorithm's expense became even more huge. So I have to give up the similarity idea.\n",
    "4. Then I tried the frequency idea. Based on Suran's algorithm, I tried different feature and parameter settings to get the highest score. As a result, the highest dev accuracy I got is 0.90072709848121835 and the highest score in Kaggle is 0.88444.\n"
   ]
  },
